    // 1. Length < n
    // 2. GCD of all elements = p

    // If a subsequence S has GCD(S) = p, then every element x in S must be a multiple of p.
    // If all elements in nums are multiples of p, then any subsequence's GCD will be a multiple of p.

    // The problem simplifies significantly if we consider only elements divisible by p.
    // Let N_p be the set of indices i such that nums[i] is a multiple of p.
    // If |N_p| < 2, we cannot form a subsequence of size >= 2, so we check for size 1.
    // However, the GCD of a single element {a} is a, so if p=a and n>1, a size 1 subsequence is good.
    // Wait, the requirement is: Length < n AND GCD = p.

    // Case 1: Subsequence of size 1: {a_i}. GCD is a_i. Good if a_i = p AND n > 1.
    // Case 2: Subsequence of size >= 2: {a_{i_1}, ..., a_{i_k}}. GCD = p. Good if k < n.

    // Observation: If there are at least two elements a_i, a_j such that gcd(a_i, a_j) = p, 
    // and if n >= 2, then {a_i, a_j} is a good subsequence (since 2 < n is possible, and if n=2, it's not good if the only good one is size 2).

    // Let's re-read the condition: "Its length strictly less than n".

    // If we find ANY subset of indices I, such that |I| < n and GCD({nums[i] | i in I}) = p, then it's a good subsequence.

    // The most restrictive case is when we have a subset whose GCD is p.
    // If we find two elements x, y such that gcd(x, y) = p, and n >= 3, then {x, y} is a good subsequence.
    // If n = 2, and we find x, y such that gcd(x, y) = p, then the only non-empty proper subset is {x} or {y}.
    // If {x} is good, x=p. If {y} is good, y=p.

    // The existence of *any* good subsequence is equivalent to:
    // 1. There exists an index i such that nums[i] = p, AND n > 1. (Size 1 subsequence)
    // OR
    // 2. There exist two indices i != j such that gcd(nums[i], nums[j]) = p, AND n > 2. (Size 2 subsequence)
    // OR
    // 3. There exists a subset of size k, 1 < k < n, whose GCD is p.

    // Since we are looking for existence, we only need to check the simplest cases: size 1 or size 2.
    // If a set S of size k > 2 has GCD(S) = p, then any pair {x, y} from S must satisfy gcd(x, y) is a multiple of p.
    // If we can find a pair whose GCD is p, we satisfy the condition if $n > 2$.
    // If $n=2$, the only proper subsequences are size 1. We need $nums[0]=p$ or $nums[1]=p$.

    // Let's simplify the condition based on the constraints $2 \le n$:

    // Condition for existence of a good subsequence:
    // A. If n=2: Good if nums[0] = p OR nums[1] = p.
    // B. If n>2: Good if:
    //    1. There exists i such that nums[i] = p. (Size 1)
    //    OR
    //    2. There exist i != j such that gcd(nums[i], nums[j]) = p. (Size 2)

    // Since checking all subsets is too slow, we rely on the fact that if a set S has GCD(S)=p, then any subset of S also has a GCD that is a multiple of p. 
    // If we find *any* subset whose GCD is p, the smallest such subset (in terms of size, or just one of size 1 or 2) is sufficient, provided its size < n.

    // If there's any element $x$ such that $x=p$, and $n>1$, we are good.
    // If there are two elements $x, y$ such that $\text{gcd}(x, y) = p$, and $n>2$, we are good.

    // If $n=2$: Good iff $nums[0]=p$ or $nums[1]=p$.
    // If $n>2$: Good iff ($\exists i, nums[i]=p$) OR ($\exists i \neq j, \text{gcd}(nums[i], nums[j])=p$).

    // Let's use this simplified check, as finding a general set GCD=p is NP-hard if we don't limit the size, but here the size constraint is $k < n$.

    let count = 0;

    for (const [ind, val] of queries) {
        // Update nums
        nums[ind] = val;

        let existsGoodSubsequence = false;

        if (n === 2) {
            // Check size 1 subsequences: {nums[0]}, {nums[1]}
            if (nums[0] === p || nums[1] === p) {
                existsGoodSubsequence = true;
            }
            // Size 2 subsequence is not allowed (length < 2 is false)
        } else { // n >= 3
            // Check size 1 subsequences
            for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                if (nums[i] === p) {
                    existsGoodSubsequence = true;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (!existsGoodSubsequence) {
                // Check size 2 subsequences
                for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                    for (let j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                        if (gcd(nums[i], nums[j]) === p) {
                            existsGoodSubsequence = true;
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    if (existsGoodSubsequence) break;
                }
            }
        }

        if (existsGoodSubsequence) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    return count;
}

